SIMPLE: cycloid
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Cycloid
<hw>Cy"cloid</hw> <pr>(s?"kloid)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Cyclo-</ets> + <ets>-oid</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>cyclo⟦ium⟧de</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A curve
generated by a point in the plane of a circle when the circle is rolled
along a straight line, keeping always in the same plane.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>common cycloid</xex> is the curve described
when the generating point (<xex>p</xex>) is on the circumference of the
generating circle; the <xex>curtate cycloid</xex>, when that point lies
without the circumference; the <xex>prolate</xex> or <xex>inflected
cycloid</xex>, when the generating point (<xex>p</xex>) lies within that
circumference.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cycloid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Cycloid
<hw>Cy"cloid</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or
pertaining to the Cycloidei.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cycloid scale</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a fish
scale which is thin and shows concentric lines of growth, without
serrations on the margin.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cycloid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Cycloid
<hw>Cy"cloid</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the
Cycloidei.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cycloidal</ent>⟦br⟧
